  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Brisbane sellers do not think much about their gas appliances during a campaign. The cooktop has worked for years; the hot water system runs hot when the tap turns; the gas log fire flickered the last time it was used in winter. None of that prevents the appliances becoming an issue at the inspection stage, where a buyer's building inspector or qualified gas plumber may flag installations that are not currently compliant, no longer have certification paperwork, or include unsafe ventilation, isolation, or flue arrangements. A small surprise at the inspection report stage can become a meaningful price reduction in a contract negotiation, or in some cases the reason a contract collapses. Sellers who walk through their gas installations before listing usually save themselves money.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the gas appliance compliance points Brisbane sellers should be aware of, what the common issues look like, where the formal certification trail sits, and how to handle the conversation with buyers when an issue is identified during the campaign. Standard caveat: this is not regulatory or licensed gas advice. Use a licensed gas fitter for any actual inspection or rectification work.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The basic Queensland framework</h2>
      <p>Gas work in Queensland (installation, alteration, disconnection, and certification of gas appliances) must be carried out by a licensed gas fitter. After completing a notifiable gas work job, the licensed gas fitter is required to issue a Gas Compliance Certificate, which serves as the formal record that the installation meets the relevant standards at the time the work was performed. For sellers, the practical implication is that any gas appliance installed or altered at the property should, in principle, have a corresponding compliance certificate held somewhere in the home's records. In practice, certificates are often missing, especially for older installations or work completed by previous owners, and that gap is one of the more common questions a buyer's solicitor or inspector raises during the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cooktops: ventilation, clearance, and isolation</h2>
      <p>Gas cooktops are the most common gas appliance in Brisbane homes. The compliance points that come up at inspection most often relate to ventilation (whether the kitchen has adequate fixed ventilation or a properly ducted rangehood), clearance (whether overhead cabinetry, splashback materials, and adjacent surfaces meet the required clearances above and beside the burners), and isolation (whether there is a clearly identified gas isolation valve accessible without dismantling cabinetry). Older cooktop installations sometimes pre-date current clearance and ventilation standards and operate safely in practice but would not meet current installation requirements if installed today. This does not necessarily mean rectification is required at sale, but it does mean a buyer's inspector may comment, and the seller should be prepared to address the comment with the right context.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Hot water systems: continuous flow, storage, and flue arrangements</h2>
      <p>Brisbane homes use a mix of continuous flow (instantaneous) gas hot water systems, gas storage tanks, and increasingly heat pumps and electric storage. Gas hot water systems are typically installed externally on a wall or pad, with a gas line, water connections, electrical connection if applicable, and a flue or vent arrangement appropriate to the unit type. Compliance issues that arise at inspection include flue terminations close to opening windows or eaves where they should not be, isolation valves that are inaccessible or seized, gas line runs that have deteriorated, and units that have exceeded their effective service life and are operating with degraded efficiency. Replacing a non-compliant or end-of-life hot water system before listing is often cheaper than negotiating a rectification credit at contract stage, especially if the unit is also visibly tired.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Instantaneous gas heaters and bayonet fittings</h2>
      <p>Some Brisbane homes have wall-mounted instantaneous gas heaters or bayonet fittings used for portable gas heaters in winter. These are less common in inner-east stock than gas cooktops or hot water systems, but they appear often enough to be worth checking. Bayonet fittings should be capped or fitted with a compliant connection if they are not in use. Wall-mounted heaters of older designs may have ventilation, flueing, or product-recall implications. If you have an unused bayonet fitting from a previous owner's gas heater, the safest position before listing is to have a licensed gas fitter inspect it and either commission it properly with a compliant appliance or cap it according to current requirements. A bayonet fitting that is left dangling behind a sofa is a small thing for a buyer's inspector to flag and an easy thing to address before the campaign begins.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Gas log fires and decorative gas appliances</h2>
      <p>A subset of inner-east homes have gas log fires installed in living rooms, often as a feature in renovations done in the 2000s and 2010s. These appliances have specific compliance requirements around flueing, room ventilation, clearances to combustible materials, and the certification of the original installation. They are also subject to ongoing servicing recommendations from manufacturers. If your home has a gas log fire and you cannot locate the original compliance certificate, having a licensed gas fitter service the unit and confirm the installation is in order is a sensible pre-listing step. Buyers love a working gas fire as a feature, especially in winter campaigns; an inoperable or visibly neglected one becomes a liability.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Gas meter and gas main connection</h2>
      <p>The gas meter and the connection from the street main is the responsibility of the network operator, but the section between the meter and the appliances is the homeowner's responsibility. Sellers should know the location of the gas meter, the location of the main isolation valve at the meter, and the routing of internal gas lines if recent renovation work has taken place. Older homes sometimes have steel gas piping that has been progressively replaced with copper or polyethylene during various renovations, which can leave a mix of materials and joints in the gas reticulation. A licensed gas fitter walking the system from the meter to each appliance can identify points of concern and recommend rectification where required.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">LPG installations: bottle storage and clearance</h2>
      <p>Some homes (particularly those without natural gas connection or in pockets of the inner east where gas mains are not available) use LPG bottles for cooking and hot water. LPG installations carry their own compliance requirements: bottle storage location, distance from windows and ignition sources, securing of bottles, signage where applicable, and the regulator and connection equipment between the bottle and the internal lines. LPG installations that have been in place for many years sometimes drift out of compliance through changes around them: an extension that put a window closer to the bottle storage, a new air-conditioning condenser unit installed nearby, or a new fence built too close to the gas cylinder cage. Sellers with LPG should have a licensed gas fitter check the installation in the months before listing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers and their inspectors will actually do</h2>
      <p>Most Brisbane buyers will engage a building and pest inspector for the property. Many will also have the gas installation looked at as part of that inspection or as a separate inspection by a licensed gas fitter, particularly where the home has multiple gas appliances or visibly older installations. Their report will typically note the make and approximate age of each appliance, the visible installation conditions, any compliance concerns observable without dismantling work, and recommendations for further investigation where they cannot make a definitive assessment from a visual inspection. The report is the primary document buyers use to negotiate price reductions or rectification works as a condition of contract. Sellers who have already addressed the obvious points before listing find these reports come back cleaner, with fewer items to negotiate over.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Documentation: what to gather before listing</h2>
      <p>The single most useful pre-listing exercise for gas appliance compliance is to gather whatever documentation already exists. Compliance certificates from previous gas work, owner's manuals, service records, receipts from the installation of the hot water system or cooktop, and any servicing reports from the gas log fire or instantaneous heater are each useful. Where certificates are missing, a record of when the appliance was installed and by whom can be partial substitute. Documentation reduces buyer uncertainty: a buyer who can see that the cooktop was installed by a licensed gas fitter four years ago with a compliance certificate is less likely to push for further investigation than a buyer who is told the cooktop has been there since the previous owner with no records.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to rectify before listing versus negotiate at contract</h2>
      <p>The economics of gas appliance issues are usually straightforward. Small items (a missing cap on a bayonet fitting, a service of a gas log fire, a replacement of an isolation valve, a new flue terminal on a hot water system) are cheap to address before listing and remove a buyer's leverage in negotiation. Larger items (replacement of an end-of-life hot water system, rectification of non-compliant flueing, removal and recapping of a redundant gas appliance) are still usually cheaper to handle as a seller-side rectification than to concede in contract negotiation, where the buyer typically asks for the cost of rectification plus a margin for the inconvenience. The exception is where the issue is genuinely contested or where the rectification scope is ambiguous; in those cases, a documented quote from a licensed gas fitter and a willingness to credit the buyer at settlement is sometimes more efficient than performing the work pre-listing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical pre-listing gas appliance walk-through</h2>
      <p>The practical pre-listing exercise looks roughly like this. Engage a licensed gas fitter for an hour or two to walk the property. Have them inspect each gas appliance, the gas meter, and the visible gas reticulation. Ask them to identify any items that would be flagged by a buyer's inspector or that present an actual safety concern. Ask for a written quote for any rectification work. Decide which items are worth completing before listing, which are worth disclosing as known and resolved with documentation, and which are worth leaving as buyer-side negotiation items with a clear cost basis. This is a few hundred dollars of professional time that, on a typical inner-east sale, comfortably pays for itself in cleaner inspection reports, smoother negotiations, and lower probability of contract issues during the cooling-off period.</p>

